Centering a `<div>` horizontally in CSS can be achieved using several methods. Here are a few common techniques:

### 1. Using `margin: auto`
This method works well when the `<div>` has a fixed width.

```html
<div class="centered-div">Content</div>
```

```css
.centered-div {
    width: 300px; /* Set a fixed width */
    margin: 0 auto; /* Center the div horizontally */
}
```

### 2. Using Flexbox
Flexbox is a powerful layout module that makes it easy to center elements.

```html
<div class="container">
    <div class="centered-div">Content</div>
</div>
```

```css
.container {
    display: flex;
    justify-content: center; /* Center the div horizontally */
}

.centered-div {
    /* No need to set a fixed width */
}
```

### 3. Using Grid Layout
CSS Grid is another modern layout system that can be used to center elements.

```html
<div class="container">
    <div class="centered-div">Content</div>
</div>
```

```css
.container {
    display: grid;
    place-items: center; /* Center the div horizontally and vertically */
}

.centered-div {
    /* No need to set a fixed width */
}
```

### 4. Using `text-align: center` (for inline elements)
If the `<div>` contains inline elements, you can use `text-align: center` on the parent element.

```html
<div class="parent">
    <div class="centered-div">Content</div>
</div>
